.TH NSPROXY 1 "February 2026" "nsproxy" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
nsproxy \- unprivileged network namespace proxy
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBnsproxy\fR [\fIOPTIONS...\fR] \fI<COMMAND>\fR [\fIARGS...\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBnsproxy\fR is a Linux\-specific command\-line tool that forces applications to use a specific SOCKS5 or HTTP proxy.
.PP
Unlike \fBtsocks\fR or \fBproxychains\fR, which use \fBLD_PRELOAD\fR to intercept library calls, \fBnsproxy\fR uses Linux network namespaces. It creates a \fBTUN\fR device in a fresh network namespace and connects it to a user\-mode TCP/IP stack (lwIP). This allows it to work with statically linked applications and avoids many of the pitfalls of \fBLD_PRELOAD\fR\-based solutions.
.PP
\fBnsproxy\fR does not require root privileges, as it leverages unprivileged user namespaces.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-H
Use HTTP proxy instead of the default SOCKS5.
.IP
.B Note:
UDP is not supported when using an HTTP proxy. UDP packets will be dropped, and an ICMP port unreachable message will be returned.
.TP
.BI \-s " server"
Proxy server address. Default is "127.0.0.1".
.TP
.BI \-p " port"
Proxy server port. Default is "1080" for SOCKS5 and "8080" for HTTP.
.TP
.BI \-d " dns"
DNS redirection. Supported values:
.RS
.IP \fBoff\fR
Do nothing with DNS; treat as normal UDP packets.
.IP \fBtcp://\fR\fIserver_ip\fR[\fB:\fR\fIport\fR]
Redirect DNS requests to the specified TCP nameserver.
.IP \fBudp://\fR\fIserver_ip\fR[\fB:\fR\fIport\fR]
Redirect DNS requests to the specified UDP nameserver.
.RE
.IP
Default is "tcp://1.1.1.1". IPv6 addresses must be enclosed in brackets (e.g., \fBtcp://[::1]:53\fR).
.TP
.BI \-a " user:pass"
Proxy authentication (SOCKS5 or HTTP Basic Auth).
.TP
.BI \-L " cidr[,cidr...]"
Connect matching destination CIDR blocks directly instead of using the proxy.
This option may be specified multiple times.
.TP
.BI \-F " file"
Load direct CIDR blocks from a file, one CIDR per line. Leading/trailing whitespace is ignored, and "#" starts a comment.
.TP
.BI \-M " whitelist|blacklist"
CIDR rule mode. In whitelist mode, matching CIDRs connect directly and other traffic uses the proxy. In blacklist mode, matching CIDRs use the proxy and other traffic connects directly. Default is whitelist.
.TP
.BI \-G " file"
Load domain rules from a file, one domain rule per line. Leading/trailing whitespace is ignored, and "#" starts a comment. Matching DNS A answers are added as /32 CIDR rules, and matching DNS AAAA answers are added as /128 CIDR rules. In whitelist mode, matching domains connect directly; in blacklist mode, matching domains use the proxy. A rule matches the exact domain and its subdomains. Prefix with "=" for exact match only. Prefix with "*." to match subdomains only.
.TP
.B \-6
Enable IPv6 support. Default is disabled.
.TP
.B \-N
Do not half-close the proxy socket when the application sends EOF. This is useful for proxy transports that cannot represent TCP half-close, such as WebSocket tunnels.
.TP
.B \-v
Verbose mode. Use "\-vv" or "\-vvv" for more verbose.
.TP
.BI \-q " [file]"
Without file, be quiet. With file, write nsproxy logs to file instead of stderr.
.TP
.B \-h
Print a help message and exit.
.SH EXAMPLES
Use SOCKS5 proxy:
.IP
\fBnsproxy curl http://example.com\fR
.PP
Use HTTP proxy:
.IP
\fBnsproxy \-H curl http://example.com\fR
.PP
Specify a custom proxy server and port:
.IP
\fBnsproxy \-s 192.168.1.100 \-p 8888 curl http://example.com\fR
.PP
Proxy most traffic, but connect private network destinations directly:
.IP
\fBnsproxy \-L 10.0.0.0/8 \-L 192.168.0.0/16 curl http://example.com\fR
.PP
Load direct CIDR blocks from a file:
.IP
\fBnsproxy \-F ./direct-cidrs.txt curl http://example.com\fR
.PP
Use CIDR rules as a blacklist, proxying only matching ranges:
.IP
\fBnsproxy \-M blacklist \-F ./proxy-cidrs.txt curl http://example.com\fR
.PP
Load domain rules and dynamically add DNS results to CIDR rules:
.IP
\fBnsproxy \-M whitelist \-G ./direct-domains.txt curl http://example.com\fR
.SH LIMITATIONS
.IP \(bu 2
All UIDs and GIDs except the current user's are mapped to the overflow UID/GID. This means programs like \fBsudo\fR or \fBsu\fR will not work.
.IP \(bu 2
It's unable to establish a connection to the inside from the outside. This means programs listening a port like \fBapache\fR or \fBnginx\fR will not work.
.IP \(bu 2
Connections to loopback addresses (\fB127.0.0.1\fR) refer to the inside of the namespace, not the host.
